{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# op-cert: AWS IaC + deploy of the trusted gate service (zero fixed-cost: existing VM + API Gateway SigV4) + live authenticated integrity test\n\n## Why\nThe trusted gate service (the sibling service story) is only a trust anchor once it runs in the\ncontrolled environment with SigV4-authenticated access and a key nobody else can read. This\nstory declares that as code, **actually deploys it** (an authenticated AWS CLI is provided — the\ndeploy is in scope), and proves the deployed endpoint end-to-end. Deployment decisions are\nsettled in the epic's \"Producer-signing & compute-runtime design resolution\", **cost-verified\nagainst the live account**: rebar's entire AWS footprint is the one t4g.large `rebar-gerrit`\nbox (+ Route 53 + free SSM parameters), so the binding constraint is **zero increase in fixed\nmonthly cost** — the service rides the existing box (the compose slot freed by the autolander's\nretirement, ADR 0047) behind an API Gateway HTTP API (pay-per-request, no fixed fee), with the\nkey in free SSM Parameter Store. A dedicated Fargate/NLB/Secrets-Manager/KMS-CMK stack was\nrejected (~$50+/mo new spend for isolation ADR 0046 L4 does not require).\n\n**Hard dependency (not yet on `main`):** the sibling service story provides\n`src/rebar/opcert_service/` and `infra/compose/Dockerfile.opcert` — neither exists on `main`\nyet; this story starts only after that story lands (enforced by the `depends_on` link).\n\n## What\n- **Terraform — extend the existing `infra/terraform/`** (the module that already declares the\n  Gerrit EC2, its IAM instance profile, and the data volume):\n  - an **API Gateway HTTP API** (v2) whose routes set `authorization_type = \"AWS_IAM\"` (SigV4\n    — a ROUTE attribute; HTTP API v2 has NO separate `aws_apigatewayv2_authorizer` resource for\n    IAM), over TLS. The integration URI is **`https://` to the box's HOST-nginx TLS origin**\n    (nginx + certbot run as HOST services on the box — `infra/scripts/compose-up.sh` header —\n    with TLS on 443 at the Elastic-IP-bound hostname; NOT `http://…:80`, which the existing\n    config 301-redirects and would break the integration) for the `/opcert/` routes, injecting a shared origin-guard header. Caller restriction is\n    identity-policy-based (an HTTP API has no resource policy): `AWS_IAM` auth requires SigV4,\n    and the IaC CREATES the admin role it restricts to — `aws_iam_role` **`rebar-opcert-admin`**\n    (no such role pre-exists in `infra/terraform/`), trust policy limited to the principal ARNs\n    supplied via a new variable `opcert_admin_principal_arns` (set at deploy to the operator's\n    IAM principals), with an inline policy granting `execute-api:Invoke` scoped to exactly this\n    API's execution ARN — and no other principal/policy in the IaC grants Invoke;\n  - an **SSM Parameter Store SecureString** `/rebar/prod/opcert-ed25519-key` (declared with a\n    placeholder `value` + `lifecycle { ignore_changes = [value] }`, so the out-of-band-seeded\n    key is never reverted or clobbered by a later `terraform apply`) holding the\n    **passphrase-free Ed25519 private key**. NO new IAM\n    grant: the parameter lives under `/rebar/prod/`, which the instance profile's existing\n    `rebar-gerrit-ssm-params-read` policy (`infra/terraform/iam.tf`) already covers — and\n    nothing broader is added;\n  - the **origin-guard header provisioning path**: Terraform generates the guard value with\n    `random_password` — the `hashicorp/random` provider is ADDED to\n    `infra/terraform/versions.tf` `required_providers` (today it pins only `hashicorp/aws\n    ~> 5.0`; `terraform init` refreshes `.terraform.lock.hcl`) — stores it as SSM SecureString\n    `/rebar/prod/opcert-origin-guard` (also under the existing grant), and maps it as a static\n    request-header parameter (`X-Opcert-Guard`) on the API Gateway integration;\n  - NO new fixed-monthly-cost resources: no Fargate/ECS service, no load balancer/VPC link, no\n    Secrets Manager secret, no customer KMS CMK, and no `kms:Sign` anywhere (SSHSIG signing is\n    performed by the service itself; AWS KMS has no Ed25519 signing).\n- **Compose — extend `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml`**: an `opcert` service on\n  `infra/compose/Dockerfile.opcert` (sibling story) with env `REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID` and the SSM\n  parameter names; an nginx route `/opcert/` → the service that rejects requests whose\n  `X-Opcert-Guard` header does not match. On the box the guard value is materialized from its\n  SSM parameter into a HOST-nginx conf include (nginx runs as a host service, not a container)\n  + the service env, by `infra/scripts/materialize-opcert-guard.sh` following the existing\n  precedent (`infra/gerrit/materialize-deploy-key.sh` / `materialize-g2p-config.sh` — SSM →\n  file). It is WIRED INTO the boot orchestrator `infra/scripts/compose-up.sh` alongside the\n  existing materialize/.env-regeneration calls, running BEFORE `docker compose up` (the\n  precedent ordering), and it finishes with `nginx -s reload` so a guard rotation re-run takes\n  effect on the host nginx (at first boot the reload is a no-op-safe refresh) — the same value Terraform maps onto the API Gateway integration, closing\n  the loop.\n- **Deploy + prove** (authenticated AWS CLI): `terraform apply`; generate the key locally\n  (`ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -N \"\"`) and seed the SecureString (the key exists nowhere else);\n  deploy the compose service on the box; pin the environment's public key + `env_id` into\n  `.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml` per the epic's era protocol; then the live checks — a\n  SigV4-signed job round-trip (submit → poll → terminal status), an unsigned request rejected\n  (401/403 at API Gateway), and a direct-to-origin request without the guard header rejected.\n## Scope\n- In: the Terraform extension, compose/nginx wiring, key generation + SSM seeding procedure,\n  the real deploy, the live round-trip evidence, the trusted-env pinning.\n- Out: the service code and Dockerfile (sibling story); any change to rebar library code; the\n  merge-gate consumer (shipped, 4214); resizing or re-homing the existing box.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `infra/terraform/` declares: the API Gateway HTTP API (v2) with\n      `authorization_type = \"AWS_IAM\"` on its routes over TLS,\n      `execute-api:Invoke` granted only to the IaC-created `rebar-opcert-admin` role (trust policy\n      from `opcert_admin_principal_arns`; the assertion method is STRUCTURED, with the literal\n      command the test runs: `terraform plan -out=tf.plan && terraform show -json tf.plan |\n      jq '[.planned_values.root_module.resources[] | select(.type == \"aws_iam_role_policy\" or\n      .type == \"aws_iam_policy\") | {name: .name, s: (.values.policy | fromjson | .Statement[])}\n      | select([.s.Action] | flatten | any(. == \"execute-api:Invoke\"))]'` — asserting the\n      resulting array has length 1 and its `name` is the `rebar-opcert-admin` invoke policy), the `hashicorp/random` provider in `required_providers`,\n      the box-origin integration with the static `X-Opcert-Guard` request-header mapping; and\n      the two SecureString parameters (the key parameter guarded by\n      `lifecycle { ignore_changes = [value] }`)\n      (`/rebar/prod/opcert-ed25519-key`, `/rebar/prod/opcert-origin-guard`) under the existing\n      `rebar-gerrit-ssm-params-read` path grant with NO new/broader IAM grant. A test asserts\n      these declarations exist.\n- [ ] `terraform fmt -check` and `terraform validate` pass (asserted by a test or CI step);\n      `terraform plan` against the provided account succeeds.\n- [ ] `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml` + nginx config gain the `opcert` service and the\n      guarded `/opcert/` route; a test asserts the service entry, the env wiring\n      (`REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID`, parameter names), that the nginx route requires the\n      `X-Opcert-Guard` header, and that the materialize script (per the `infra/gerrit/materialize-*.sh`\n      precedent) renders the guard value from its SSM parameter — tested hermetically with a\n      stub `aws` executable prepended to `PATH` that returns a fixture value (no live SSM or\n      account access in unit tests). The test also asserts `infra/scripts/compose-up.sh` calls\n      the materialize script before `docker compose up`, that the script ends with\n      `nginx -s reload` (host nginx), and that the Terraform integration URI uses the\n      `https://` scheme.\n- [ ] The deployed environment's public key and `env_id` are pinned in\n      `.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml` (with `added_at_commit` per the epic's era protocol); a\n      test asserts the entry parses and the `env_id` matches the compose service's\n      `REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID`.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The service is deployed from `infra/` via the authenticated AWS CLI\n      and the live checks pass: a SigV4-signed job round-trip succeeds; an unsigned request is\n      rejected at API Gateway; a direct-to-origin request without the guard header is rejected —\n      evidence: a comment recording the `terraform apply` outputs (API endpoint id/URL) and the\n      captured round-trip + both rejections."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784025138135066001,"uuid":"ce375016-226a-4577-b68f-12dcc0cb4f06"}